  "doc_id": "4293",
  "text": "Even if previous studies (e.g., Marquar et al. [CITATION_1] ) report that individuals usually associated increased fiber intake with the main health benefits of eating whole-grain foods, our results suggest that other health-promoting components (i.e., B vitamins that help to reduce fatigue) have a greater impact in influencing the consumption of whole grains. Our findings also suggest how psychological health claims of whole grains seem more attractive than physiological health claims for university students. Several possible explanations could be drawn. First, the target population might be more interested in \"scholarly\" benefits, such as the reduction of fatigue, rather than weight management. Nonetheless, it is likely that the information provided will be more effective when it addresses specific needs to the target population [CITATION_2] . Moreover, when a decision-making process occurs between a long-term benefit (e.g., 'maintain a healthy weight') and a short-term benefit (e.g., 'be more alert'), the latter outcome is likely to be more preferred [CITATION_3] .",
